				\begin{document} $${}\begin{aligned} \eta_{i} &= \beta x_{i} + \sum_{p=1}^{P} w^{\mathsf{T}}_{ip} \gamma_{p} + \delta_{1,\mathsf{sex}[i]} x_{i} + \delta_{2,\mathsf{age}[i]} x_{i} + \delta_{3,\mathsf{cmb}[i]} x_{i}\\ &\quad+ \delta_{4,\mathsf{O2}[i]} x_{i} \end{aligned} $$ \end{document}ηi=βxi+∑p=1PwipTγp+δ1,sex[i]xi+δ2,age[i]xi+δ3,cmb[i]xi+δ4,O2[i]xi where each δg parameter corresponds to a vector of parameters associated with each subgroup of interest with δg∼Normal(0,σδ) and σδ∼Exponential(1) such that the interaction terms are estimated under the assumption of a common variance [30]. The abbreviations “cmb” and “O2” correspond to “comorbidity” and “oxygen requirement”, respectively. Unfortunately, little information about the heterogeneity in treatment effects was available to inform the choice of prior for σδ. Hence, this prior was selected on the basis that it should impose some level shrinkage for moderately variable treatment effects.

From the above model, each covariate can be considered separately and standardised treatment effects obtained in each subgroup as weighted averages. For example, to obtain a standardised treatment effect for males, compute 
